A republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy because of the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers this a myth and states that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die because of the fall of a ray.
In fact, Republican lawyers have not found more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that regard, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what is happening in Canada, American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line, a majority of American governments enacted, from 2009 onwards, new laws that made the process of registration or voting difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights were introduced in 2011 in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce pre-voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit a photographed identity document.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
Consequently, the republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photographed identity document.
It is important to bear in mind that, unlike what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photographed identity documents issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often obtaining the required identity card costs more than a hundred dollars.
New restrictions therefore disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens aged over 65 and 20 per cent of voters aged between 18 and 29 do not have a photographed identity document.
And there's still more.
In many states students, voters who vote the most for democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with a photograph issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who often vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by these clubs.
Before 2004, no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present this requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Spanish vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for electors who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, electoral registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 resulted in a drop in the registration rate for new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that favoured the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33 per cent of the electors who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13 per cent of the state's electors.
In the case of Hispanics it was exactly the same thing.
These represent only 11 per cent of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24 per cent of the citizens voting in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens voting in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of electors.
In this regard, democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Prosecutor ' s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photographed identity document.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democrat critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, since it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed at the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty whether these legislative changes at electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this respect, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
