Anyway, we suppose it's Higgs, because the chances of making a mistake seem small. We'll see what this is about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because it will end up harming itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same quantum state, a \"state\", which is largely composed of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called ferrets, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And on the other hand are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories' Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of whom we will not speak here, and the \"power particles\" by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I would stress here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the \"light particle\" that acts as \"messenger\" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it \"disorders\" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this - disorder - an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons - force bearers -
Most stable field
It is the same with Higgs' boson, with the difference that it is about another field, Higgs' field, which needs to be \"disordered\" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it requires extremely high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the large hadron collider is a 27 km circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself attached to the door of a refrigerator.
