In recent days, a wave of protests against low wages has been launched in the Walmart corporation supermarkets and in restaurants of popular fast food chains such as \"McDonald's\" -Burger King - - Taco Bell - - Wendy's - and -Kentucky Fried Chicken - in the United States.
For now no one dares to assert whether or not this wave will reach the nine points, or whether it is destined to lose strength and dawn in its early stages.
Protest actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to increasing the modest wages earned by Walmart's workers and those of the fast food system, the goal of protest organizers is to create workers' unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has practically not been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after the Thanksgiving, the so-called \"Black Friday\" on that day, in the United States was co-embracing the orgy of lowlands that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by clashes.
On that day, some employees of the Walmart corporation, who employs 2.2 million people worldwide, abandoned their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside left-wing unions and activists in the corporate stores, whose products are aimed at modest and moderate income people.
Walmart sells everything, from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries, to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in their shops are of an average of 8% to 27% cheaper than those in larger supermarkets.
That's why many badly paid Walmart workers buy only at work.
The availability and output of products have made Walmart one of America's largest corporations.
According to two critics, Walmart can afford the luxury of selling products at very low prices, partly because he pays little to his workers.
The latter also complain of poor working conditions, such as lack of mounting or hand scanners.
That - Black Friday - the participants in the demonstration demanded the increase in wages and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation went from $30 to $100 per month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who receives $9.5 an hour, this spending is excessive, they said.
California University scientists at Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average salary up to $12 an hour, this will cost the corporation $3.2 billion.
This is approximately 1.1% more than it spends on wages now.
If Walmart puts the wage increase on consumers' shoulders, every visit to the store will result in only 46 cents more expensive.
In one year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they spend now.
Walmart's supporters comment satisfied that the protest took place only in nine states and that it did not cause any loss to the corporation.
