\"For now, deceiving the brain isn't so easy.\"
The theme of augmented reality, so popular among modern technology fans, is recently perceived with normality mainly through the prism of special glasses.
Early in the summer, at its annual Google conference, a model was shown in motion and later, in November, it was known that Microsoft had also submitted an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group in the Cambridge Microsoft laboratory, Izadi Sharamom, it was diluted that for the scientists of that company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted by the perspective of manipulation of virtual objects in the air with bare hands and the creation of open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of your research group's study?
- We are dedicated to personal-computer interaction, but we also try to broaden the boundaries of this interaction.
For now humanity in its large mass has been trapped in the working stage with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years forward and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in controlling for gestures.
- What else will the future hold for us?
- Although Kinect has led the interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The introduction of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is not very good yet.
We are trying to change this, we work on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design systems.
The world must be liberated from computer science to our physical, make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, hell with those silly virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course you can't be considered a panacea, you are still waiting to resolve the privacy issue, since you don't always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each one in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter.
In addition, gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a bracelet clock.
But in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this soda can?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- Usually I just talk.
- Oh, that's going to be very hard to recognize.
- I mean, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do right now?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I believe that in the near future we will have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine the person's reactions.
These can, for example, be laser sensors, as they provide a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do you lack resolution, depth or anything else?
- In principle, the present generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at the speed of 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
That is, we have to remember not only the resolution in X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Speed, number of frames per second, is also important.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current of 30 fps are truly scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our laboratory in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay from 1 to 100 ms and it can be mentioned that modern serial-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects man-machine interaction.
It would be very useful to me for my work to be an equivalent of such a device, but not to require contact so that the tables per second are more.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three cameras, one of which is in fact the infrared beam emitter and the second the reflected signal receiver.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible diaphragm sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or on the contrary, increase and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be good to create a flexible analogue of Kinect, play with the location curvature of the cameras and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- So I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Does it not seem to you that, from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding a smart phone high in your hands, it's not very convenient, but I think: the best option would be an increased, transmutable reality when, on the basis of a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to the smart phone,
The glasses are very personal devices, in that is your strength (private things only you can see them), but also your weakness: an increased reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects along with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark of the film - Iron Man - but also to any simple mortal.
There is a problem in this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile response!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my conferences I often say that the augmented reality is the seventh burst in the interaction between man and the machine.
I think the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand in quality support for the image.
Register the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really oriented to providing tangibleness to these - images in the air - for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is given a similar feeling to that one feels if someone was blowing it in the herds, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should feel at the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
Here is another challenge with which we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space creates that it goes to an open, almost endless space. We are also working on the idea of running tapes (not like gymnasiums), mobile platforms, as well as that of giant balloons.
For now, tricking the brain isn't that easy, you still have to work for many years.
That is what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, which many things are in a state of total conception.
