How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized otherwise?
As for the offices, like the NKU, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a college also, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve parallelly.
The competences are also to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of accounts are even at this level. In this aspect it is slightly different from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As far as local legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would generally not like to establish a comparison without specific data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be accurately defined in what is best.
Could it be better, for example, for the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but I repeat, I don't like making such comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't make them any benefit to collaborate with our office, would it?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office? Is its impact expressed in any way?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post controls, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool of - non-economic risk detection - by which we have passed almost 14,000 public procurements, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of selection and the same process are corrected.
Do you consider that the adoption of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a scam for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem may arise is that the regulation - if it hardens - and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the above regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the Regional Council), and each law not respected in the field of public procurement meant breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
A system of this kind will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We'll see where this path leads us.
The Prime Minister recently stated that the ODS would not bother employers with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being self-governing only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the Government can prevent the Office from acting under the obligation to carry out such controls and to require obligations.
You can say, \"We change the law and we allow it,\" but you can't say that we'll do it as if nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the legislation is quite strict as to how it should be acted formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
