Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week, Poland was accepted as a twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member country of ESA of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and participated in the agency's project commission in the following years.
However, the way from Poland to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study \"Introduction to cosmonautica\"
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch award in France for its \"Introduction to cosmonautica\"
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a cosmonautic promoter, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the craters on the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a drain was built in Poland and was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who the author of the proposal was, and the highlights of the project are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the drain or for braking.
The information about this drain is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
Starting in 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is evident that the research reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 it appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński and the following year was published the study \"Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza\" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committeeet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all draft missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, of Prof. M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics was proposed.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since early 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronomical Studies (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and air tests of two-stage RM-2 rockets in the Błędów desert began in the summer of 1959.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed by the space available to scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests were started in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg to 60 km high.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 version was subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the investigation of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonauta after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the problem that exists from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
This means, therefore, that the different forms of economics and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is found in the principle of free trade and free and unlimited private capital movement, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so - it causes a downside - of the price of the competitor in order to be made with most of the market and thus increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most employers, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where labour prices, compared to other economies, are higher.
Due to the fact that private capital has no social responsibility and is therefore not responsible for the unemployment caused by this phenomenon, the social expenditure of the state is necessarily increasing.
This whole situation fosters the total disinterest of employers for paying taxes and compensates for the economic and social damage they have caused in their quest for benefits.
The situation is so universally known that there is no need to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is particularly evident in changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the private capital dictatorship, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees in respect of labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people who receive this kind of help is already up to a million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with such low wages that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of virtually all the southern states of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abismal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live with a poor wage on the edge of society, hoping that one day they will reach the country's private investor capital.
Do you need to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty moves from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European wage.
This also affects all Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media assert to the satire that the state should not bring capital to the economy, which leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by interfering in control.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence its selfishness in the political march and, therefore, in the whole state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in very powerful and omnipresent practice, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills for private legal enterprises, which are often linked to industry.
These kinds of bills are later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation are rapidly in a situation like the one describing Appiànos in his work The crisis of the Roman republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: \"The state was taking time disintegrating and the administrations occupied themselves with force.\"
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained unlawfully and aid to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread unhindered and the people came to the polls with the vote applauded in advance - ... - there were no people of character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls -... -He began to talk seriously that the only remedy for such a situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose a energetic man -... Although Appiannos thought in Pompeya, Caesar came up to power and turned democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, in the same way as in ancient times, is that the current society is based on unconsidered preferences of the individual benefit without taking account of the common interests.
Private capital is essentially unable to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as that of then, a decline in the unprecedented elite, without an effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of the fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next blow.
The real thing is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes of which we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
