The MVRDV architecture studio shows that the real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed - Book Mountain - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a street passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, a IT technician in a large company located near the library, points out: \"In addition, the building is beautiful\"
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody gets into those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, boasts the dubious honor of having stood up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, some years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And this was how policymakers decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a whole master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings to the pair that cynics, took the theme with its usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under the arm and a smile on the face.
And while the jury looked around and shuddered with shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words:-Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, the so-called \"Boekenberg\" -
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November, the mountain of books was awarded the second prize -Best Library of NL 2012 -
In addition, the project is also nominated for the “Dutch National Wood Award 2012”
In this way, the small town lacking history, which to date had nothing but to offer that a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly township behind whose white façade one would institute a central dairy, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheesepot.
It is true that there is an elevator that carries us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climbing to the top.
The fully crystallized interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor picked up and the elegant headlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Upon raising the view you can get to view the banks of the park, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“The book shelves are usually arranged along the facade and in the center there is a huge dark room that usually is uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put the classical spatial configuration on top and remove the reading area from the interior to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and barricade at the same time.
The view, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more day by day shake their heads when they hear of this unknown material.
\"We wanted to work with recycled materials,\" Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse explains.
And this is like one day, on a frying farm, we meet with the proper by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and camps of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of only a few millimetres of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is cheap and efficient material.
This thin tissue lasts for two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library this fabric was first taken in such quantities until it obtained four-centimeter thick plates.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells of a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 pellets you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the coffee shop not only you have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy a tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant, even atmosphere that maintains the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
\"Even if it is hard to believe it because of its large crystallized surfaces, this building is an exemplary project with regard to ecology,\" Trouborst says.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge pyramid of crystal, even in the sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located cross-section to the glass façade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable interior climate.
The rest is the thing about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptic information technology worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Likewise, the traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She qualifies the \"Boekenberg\" as the \"late soul\" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, because of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, at the moment, the optical gaps in a library that does not yet have its complete file; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has fallen deep.
The shelves are full.
\"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library,\" architect Winy Maas says.
\"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even though he's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a complete success in that discipline, which in the specialized slang is known as the creation of an identity.
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uneducated it may be.
At last a starting point to make up your identity.
