I think they're still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they've already started the way to a normal foreign policy.
A similar foreign policy to countries such as France or Great Britain.
What does a German-speaking foreign policy really mean?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, stands ready to defend different positions than those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated in economic policy, i.e. in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers, and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful and not alienate from the Arab public opinion nor from the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it that importance since it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining from voting in important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
