Bradley Manning has not reported ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuses during his stay in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period in Quantico's military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leaking of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while under military detention.
During the interrogation the prosecution conducted at Manning in a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, the prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of officers of the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which was conducted during a hearing conducted following the defence ' s request that the case be dismissed as his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already been sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of suicide while he was in custody.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is charged with stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In the view of Friday, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after the visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was in prison under maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the celebrators as \"excellent\" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as \"very professional\"
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had talked about those problems and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not leave any record of those issues on the record.
\"They wrote 'no incidences' (after talking about problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I would not have mentioned any problems,\" Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she had received during the January 2011 meeting with a council to examine the suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the injury prevention regime under which he was under.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is a degree below the possible suicide surveillance, to ensure their protection and safety of others.
“I wanted the higher state to know that I was okay and (I wanted to) stop being under injury prevention... in order to enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the Marines in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness because of the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening to him in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to the Arafjon Camp, to that cage,” Manning explained on Thursday.
\"I thought I was going to die in that cage.\"
Manning said that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some heels, some clothes and their glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since he was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the blinds couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in the statement of Thursday, according to which, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell of Quantico, he was forced during a morning count to remain bare in front of the jailers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the questioning of the judge on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order given by the locksmith that he should have dropped the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his heels to self-harm but that he had not done so.
Manning testified that that night they had taken their underwear, their heels and their glasses out of their cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he has experienced during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he is convicted on the war council, which is expected to begin early next year.
The defence stated that Manning is planning to make Manning guilty of minor offences and to defend other charges considered to be too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detainee who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully causing the publication of information on the Internet, filtering information from the national defence and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
